The building is positioned at the end of the platforms and has two towers in front, one for each corner, all resembling a typical German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The building in your compound is a little run down.
But once the box office was vaulted, there was no doubt whatever the greatness of the enterprise that this was the westernmost door.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation consortium.
Germany, a latecomer in the imperial game, had the ambition to dominate the Middle East through this railway that stretched to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during World War I.
Their railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has led to the fall of the
British rule and when the forces advanced into Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was bad for the Hyderpasha station as well.
In 1917 a train of ammunition exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources said it was sabotage.
Since then the station has been decaying and has been left on the sidelines of history.
But today, this railway, the gateway to Anatolia and all the Eastern centres, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's willingness to broaden its diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there's a new policy of collaboration.
The Turkish Government maintains excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I got on a bunk and went to the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the leaders of the AKP, an expert on foreign policy, the Turkish Prime Minister Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a journey of shaking, which produced the cadence of the ancient world in the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - a new city, designed to govern a new secular state, far from the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its clear Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
It has aroused some suspicion in the West and especially in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and steel structure - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-built shopping malls and "power bakeries" where middle-class managers in business suits - men and women - meet early in the morning to make deals.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
"The goal of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighborhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its internal relations.
Today you have to look at the same time to the East and the West.
It's not a case if it's not one way or the other.
You have to do both.
"But surely at some point", I ask, "Turkey might be forced to choose?"
"Turkey", he replies, "does not want to face that choice".
He then underlines a point which almost everyone I have spoken to up to now had recited to me almost from memory: Turkey's relations with the Middle East, the Caucasus region and the entire Black Sea region are a benefit for Europe and the United States as well as for Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe as a whole can metaphorically build those railway lines that open up the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after a second sleepless night, my thoughts return to the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had witnessed the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised would you have been to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East were now largely in the hands of Turkey?
And waiting at the terminal for the ferry that will take me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered "the sick man of Europe".
So there is little doubt as to what the continent will be that this fascinating country must claim.
