The Bee Car that Avoids Collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, specifically bees.
A Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, prevents accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technology Center have developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, general manager of PR for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an expansion of Nissan's four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to strengthen the collision prevention capability of the brand's vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal space in an oval shape that closely resembles the Nissan Safety Shield.
But most important are the bee's compound eyes, able to see at an angle of over 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly uninterrupted within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser rangefinder.
It detects obstacles up to two metres away within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor, which immediately prevents the collision.
"The minute it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at right angles or higher to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the evasion maneuver is totally instinctive.
Otherwise, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and lead engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be deflected up or down, nor diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to spin its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, to prevent the small robot from colliding.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It requires no storage of information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can run continuously with only a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even mega".
This is the first step in developing new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced in production cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the lithium ion variety.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination avoiding obstacles on the road.
