Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refound the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is a joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, following the example of his colleagues and friends, he is the third to put to the vote a draft for a new Constitution.
Mission accomplished, with 64% of voters voting 'yes' to the referendum, according to official results which referred to 80% of the votes cast.
According to these results, the "no" won 28%, 7% of the votes were void and 0.7% were blank.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to get half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two exit polls and a count by a non-governmental organization announced a broad victory for the "yes" vote, estimating it at between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed in the night of Sunday to Monday the victory of his draft Constitution.
"The Constitution has triumphed overwhelmingly", he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who head the government in Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Thus, Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will be held in complete calm, according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), referred to a text of 444 points that consolidated the "new socialism" advocated by the president.
The draft constitution implies the increase of the power of the State over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to foreign currency sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the bill also grants strengthened powers to the head of state, who can serve up to two consecutive four-year terms and has the possibility to dissolve the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the President has begun to implement in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It finally provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for US anti-drug operations.
The 19 people kidnapped in Chad have been released
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the 11 tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The 11 European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions kidnapped ten days ago in the desert arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
By morning, they had been released by Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked fine when they arrived at 3:30 p.m. aboard a special plane at the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately flown by helicopter to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical tests, so they have not been able to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying an off-road safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since moved from one Zulu to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, which organised the safari.
An Egyptian security official said 30 special forces personnel, transported on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of gunfire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest have fled", said the official who kept his name anonymous.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
The Italian Foreign Minister, Franco Frattini, spoke in Belgrade of the role played by Italian secret agents and special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men from the secret services, the special forces", he said without elaborating.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The Sudanese army said on the eve of the attack that it had intercepted an SUV carrying the kidnappers, killing six, including the Chadian chief, and arresting two.
He also claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement-Unity (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by the group.
Letters - The Silent Majority of Culture
A debate on the financing of culture has made headlines and is taking up the current election campaign.
It's better this way.
But one area of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable sums being given to small museums, archives, archaeological digs or starving national historic sites?
What politician will dare remind the federal government that it neglects its monuments and heritage buildings?
Why don't we have real laws that actually preserve our heritage like in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government is devoting three and a half million euros to restoring only the Château de Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in their Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of Americans and that this heritage has to be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and all this, in concert.
In Quebec, at the Federation of Quebec Historical Societies, at least 40,000 benevolent people in 211 historical, heritage, archival and genealogical societies are concerned with researching history, preserving at little cost piles of private archives and preserving archaeological remains.
These are the ones who are often the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with energy and desperation when promoters and officials throw their bulldozers at our old stones and our forgotten cemeteries.
For when, a monument to history and heritage?
The Dutch governments nationalize part of Fortis Bank.
The Netherlands - the first in Europe - will help to nationalise the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which is in difficulty as a result of the impact of the US mortgage crisis. The three countries will support the financial and insurance institution, which also has operations in Hungary, with a total of EUR 11.2 billion.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held high-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commission's chief economic adviser.
Fortis Bank was the first to suffer the euro area crisis in the context of the international financial crisis which has been occurring in several waves for over a year, and therefore the decisions taken in respect of the Bank can in some sense be considered precedent-setting.
According to the decision taken early Sunday, the three countries will buy about half (49 percent) of the Bank's property in their area.
The Bank will most likely sell part of its business, including mainly the activities - mainly insurance - bought last year from the Dutch ABN Amro.
Fortis' shares started a steep decline last week and by the second half of the week, there were already important signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees this bank is too big to allow itself to go bust.
The company's shares fell 12 percent on Friday alone, the lowest in 14 years.
Since January the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
Looking at current share prices, the total value of the group's capital on the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company's executives this is not real.
The Bank's management attributed the sharp drop in Fortis' shares to the uncertainties in the North American market in connection with the approval of the US $700 billion package plan.
On Monday, the stock showed a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the new CEO of the bank.
The Bank also sought private investors, but so far no one has made a concrete offer.
The Belgian Government had previously assured investors that they had nothing to worry about, they would not lose their money.
The Bank's customers have not been in any panic, they have not invaded the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also bought leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
In the United States, life and health insurance companies, when looking at drug purchase data, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy policy experts fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
"There are programmes for the protection of personal data, which in all cases link the use of prescription data to the consent of the person concerned.
It must be in independent hands, or else "we leave the chicken coop to the fox", says Richard Dick, designer of the prescription tracking program, as quoted by the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the price of insurance and the amount of compensation depend on the health status of the customer and if they think the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
Before sending the client to a medical check-up and signed the contract with him knowing the result of the check-up.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer's identification number he easily gets from pharmacies the list of medicines purchased in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the patient's illnesses and health status.
For example, if you regularly take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is practically incurably high, so you are immediately placed in a higher risk category.
There are many versions of the programme, some even setting a risk number, so the insurance company besides the administration has little to do, although there are some difficulties.
The disadvantages of the programme include the fact that some medicines are multi-use, for example certain substances are used both to treat headaches and heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk-increasing factor for insurance companies while the former is not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which, before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
The authorities are already forcing them to do this, although they have not been fined for their negligence so far.
Some companies have recently also produced lab test results and combined them with drug use data to obtain more accurate information about the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is an exclusive law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and healthcare providers.
The bill giving the authority the right to control companies specialised in the provision of personal data is already before the Congress.
Dick Richard recognises that this is insufficient: he therefore developed his programme, which will require specific consent from the person for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot refuse his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the chickens are, after all, exposed to the fox's goodwill.
