The European Union doubles its trade with India
As the European Union and India are mutual trading partners, this issue, in addition to other largely global issues, dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, to discuss mainly cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a major developing democratic power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs, member countries have yet to reach a common denominator on whether to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This question was not discussed at the ninth summit which began yesterday in Marseilles.
The French President Nicolas Sarkozy, President-in-Office of the EU, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission, and Javier Solana, High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and reached an agreement to double their trade to over 100 billion euros in five years.
This is not an overly ambitious objective, given that trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007.
The 26 existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India have been legally harmonized, so that air transport can fly in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The objective is balance, because while the EU is India's number one trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the Union's trading partners.
The summit focused on global affairs.
Both sides condemned the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and terrorism in all its forms and called for a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha trade liberalization round was also pressed, although both sides bear a heavy responsibility for its failure.
The EU confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, meaning that by 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least twenty per cent.
India is also in agreement with this, just as at the climate conference next year a global agreement should be reached and greenhouse gas emissions should be reduced by 50 percent by 2050.
They also want to prevent food prices from rising and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
Today the Indian Prime Minister will travel to the French capital, where - in a bilateral meeting - he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
Paris is confident that French companies will receive contracts worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
