Found the plane of Steve Fossett the millionaire who disappeared a year ago
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris has been found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the area of the Nevada Sierra of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson has dispelled any remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squad, and now we have confirmation that it is the same one that Steve Fossett was flying over the day he disappeared", he said at a press conference.
The Commissioner has said that no human remains have been found either on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was pronounced dead in February.
The US Transportation Safety Board (TSB) has announced that a team of investigators has been sent to identify the aircraft, which was a Bellanca 8kcab, which was lost since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada, on a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal remains were found by a couple near his Mammoth Lakes home.
It's two documents in Fossett's name, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweater.
The search for Fossett had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had earned a place in history through a long string of firsts.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he had become the first man to complete a round-the-world flight in a hot air balloon: two weeks of solitary flight.
Three years later, I had circumnavigated the globe by plane, nonstop.
Among his records, he also had the distinction of flying over the Andes at 15,445 meters, but with a co-pilot.
